SPEAKER 1: At least, that's
what I think is accurate.

00:37:06.090 --> 00:37:09.120
AUDIENCE: I had a question
about, I guess, philosophy.

00:37:09.120 --> 00:37:12.570
You seem to have some
experience there.

00:37:12.570 --> 00:37:16.800
Who have you read, or
who are your influences,

00:37:16.800 --> 00:37:19.800
both science fiction writers
and if there's anybody,

00:37:19.800 --> 00:37:22.350
contemporary philosophers.

00:37:22.350 --> 00:37:25.445
DENNIS E. TAYLOR: In terms
of philosophers, I haven't--

00:37:28.020 --> 00:37:32.910
I mean, I have listened
to "Plato's Republic"

00:37:32.910 --> 00:37:36.677
and I've read some of the
philosophy of Socrates

00:37:36.677 --> 00:37:37.510
and stuff like that.

00:37:37.510 --> 00:37:41.940
But mostly, it's
research oriented.

00:37:41.940 --> 00:37:44.700
I'm a very pragmatic person.

00:37:44.700 --> 00:37:47.130
So I tend to read what I
need to read in order to get

00:37:47.130 --> 00:37:50.040
to where I want to get to.

00:37:50.040 --> 00:37:53.220
I love "The Good Place", though.

00:37:53.220 --> 00:37:56.520
If anybody has not watched
that, it is well worth watching,

00:37:56.520 --> 00:37:57.180
very well done.

00:38:01.460 --> 00:38:02.540
Yeah.

00:38:02.540 --> 00:38:03.920
I've actually
downloaded a couple

00:38:03.920 --> 00:38:08.570
of Audible books on philosophy
specifically for the research

00:38:08.570 --> 00:38:12.860
that I did on the Bobiverse
and on "Singularity Trap".

00:38:12.860 --> 00:38:17.990
In terms of authors, I think
my two biggest influences

00:38:17.990 --> 00:38:24.820
are Heinlein and
Niven, although there's

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:27.940
a large smattering of
Campbell and Hamilton

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:29.793
and everybody else
like that, too.

00:38:29.793 --> 00:38:30.460
SPEAKER 1: Nice.

00:38:30.460 --> 00:38:32.770
Mine are Orson Scott Card
and Dennis E. Taylor.

00:38:35.630 --> 00:38:36.890
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:38:36.890 --> 00:38:41.270
To pick up on that,
you're an avid reader.

00:38:41.270 --> 00:38:44.300
You have been an avid reader of
science fiction all your life

00:38:44.300 --> 00:38:46.970
since you were young.

00:38:46.970 --> 00:38:51.290
Do you find yourself sometimes
taking too much of ideas

00:38:51.290 --> 00:38:54.200
that you've read in the
past, and you find yourself

00:38:54.200 --> 00:38:56.690
incorporating them and you have
to stop and say, what can I

00:38:56.690 --> 00:39:00.200
do to make it my own?

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:01.880
DENNIS E. TAYLOR:
That actually isn't

00:39:01.880 --> 00:39:06.200
as much of a problem in
general as most people think.

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:13.610
As they say in the writing
industry, ideas are cheap.

00:39:16.130 --> 00:39:20.750
It's the execution of the
idea that makes the book.

00:39:20.750 --> 00:39:25.930
"The Martian" is just
"Robinson Crusoe", right?

00:39:25.930 --> 00:39:29.820
In fact, you can probably--

00:39:29.820 --> 00:39:34.470
well, if you look at any
half dozen science fiction

00:39:34.470 --> 00:39:36.000
or thriller movies--

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:41.010
"Deep Star Six",
"Leviathan", "Alien"--

00:39:41.010 --> 00:39:43.350
they're all the same theme.

00:39:43.350 --> 00:39:45.390
Bunch of people get
stuck in a limited space

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:49.260
with a monster that's
eating them one at a time.

00:39:49.260 --> 00:39:53.520
It's a very simple idea,
but how you execute it.

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:55.290
"Deep Star Six", "Alien".

00:39:57.833 --> 00:39:59.500
AUDIENCE: I actually
have two questions.

00:39:59.500 --> 00:40:02.010
One is about the
audiobook itself.

00:40:02.010 --> 00:40:02.580
I loved it.

00:40:02.580 --> 00:40:05.850
I actually listened to all
your books while I was biking

00:40:05.850 --> 00:40:07.770
and the narrator
reporter did a fantastic

00:40:07.770 --> 00:40:10.980
job, where all of these things
I can still remember them.

00:40:10.980 --> 00:40:12.540
So my question
is, how much input

00:40:12.540 --> 00:40:16.500
does author have that goes
into the narration of the book?

00:40:16.500 --> 00:40:19.330
And you also mentioned you were
editing your book for Audible.

00:40:19.330 --> 00:40:21.390
I'm wondering what kind
of editing happens there,

00:40:21.390 --> 00:40:22.932
and if you had that
in your mind when

00:40:22.932 --> 00:40:26.670
you were writing that book,
The Bobiverse universe.

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:28.630
My second question is around--

00:40:28.630 --> 00:40:30.240
and I apologize for
using the word--

00:40:30.240 --> 00:40:31.862
the books would feel
a little rushed.

00:40:31.862 --> 00:40:32.820
There's a lot of stuff.

00:40:32.820 --> 00:40:35.755
Like you could have
made it a ten-book arc.

00:40:35.755 --> 00:40:37.380
There's a lot of
stuff like the Madeira

00:40:37.380 --> 00:40:39.600
or the Chinese contingent
first contact story that

00:40:39.600 --> 00:40:41.040
would be great to know about.

00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:42.510
Is there any plan
for a collection

00:40:42.510 --> 00:40:44.370
of short stories in
the Bobiverse universe

00:40:44.370 --> 00:40:47.040
that talks about those things,
even the fall of civilization

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:48.860
and those kind of stuff?

00:40:48.860 --> 00:40:50.015
DENNIS E. TAYLOR: OK.

00:40:50.015 --> 00:40:51.390
SPEAKER 1: That's
a big question.

00:40:51.390 --> 00:40:52.980
DENNIS TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:40:52.980 --> 00:40:56.645
Well, let's answer
the second one first.

00:40:56.645 --> 00:40:58.020
I think the reason
that the books

00:40:58.020 --> 00:41:01.730
would feel rushed really
comes down to my inexperience

00:41:01.730 --> 00:41:02.730
when I was writing them.

00:41:06.140 --> 00:41:08.960
Inexperienced
writers will either

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:13.190
tend to underwrite or
overwrite massively.

00:41:13.190 --> 00:41:18.530
And part of learning the craft
is getting the mix right.

00:41:18.530 --> 00:41:23.220
I'm an underwriter, massive
underwriter by nature.

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:26.030
My first draft of a book
will be 40,000 words

00:41:26.030 --> 00:41:29.750
and then I have to figure
out how to fill it in

00:41:29.750 --> 00:41:31.200
to make it 80,000 words.

00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:34.985
And it usually consists
of things like dialogue.

00:41:38.330 --> 00:41:42.590
But yeah, it really comes
down to inexperience.

00:41:42.590 --> 00:41:46.610
If I rewrote these, I would
put a lot more detail in.

00:41:46.610 --> 00:41:50.090
I would spend a lot more
time on some of the subplots.

00:41:50.090 --> 00:41:54.140
And as far as short
stories and stuff

00:41:54.140 --> 00:41:56.220
like that, yeah, that's
definitely a plan.

00:41:56.220 --> 00:41:58.250
I've got novel ideas.

00:41:58.250 --> 00:42:02.150
I've got short story ideas,
and they'll all come together.

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:11.620
To answer the
first question, I'm

00:42:11.620 --> 00:42:14.170
sure that a big author
like John Scalzi

00:42:14.170 --> 00:42:18.160
could demand a particular
narrator if he wanted to

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:20.290
and get away with it.

00:42:20.290 --> 00:42:24.280
As a newb, I had no
say, although I suppose

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:27.700
if I'd kicked up a fuss--

00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:28.390
well, maybe not.

00:42:28.390 --> 00:42:29.360
I don't know.

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:31.600
Anyway, I had no idea who
Ray Porter was anyway,

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:34.570
so I was in no position
to do any kicking.

00:42:34.570 --> 00:42:39.820
As it turns out, I'm very
glad they picked him.

00:42:39.820 --> 00:42:44.170
Before he started on
the recordings, though,

00:42:44.170 --> 00:42:48.880
Ray contacted me, and he asked
me how some of these characters

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:51.130
sounded to me in my head.

00:42:51.130 --> 00:42:56.190
And Guppy is obvious.

00:42:56.190 --> 00:42:59.980
He sounds like Akbar.

00:42:59.980 --> 00:43:04.990
Butterworth I heard sounding
like Colonel Fowler in "Chicken

00:43:04.990 --> 00:43:06.750
Run".

00:43:06.750 --> 00:43:09.000
And Ray pulled it off.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:10.770
I mean, he really pulled it off.

00:43:10.770 --> 00:43:16.710
Homer sounded to me like Bill
Murray in "Ghostbusters",

00:43:16.710 --> 00:43:17.820
for instance.

00:43:17.820 --> 00:43:19.020
Stuff like that.

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:24.040
Most of them, though,
he just went with it.

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:27.270
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
overwriting and underwriting

00:43:27.270 --> 00:43:29.910
as one of the lessons you
learned in the process.

00:43:29.910 --> 00:43:31.260
Is there anything else?

00:43:31.260 --> 00:43:34.230
Like overall, has your
process for writing

00:43:34.230 --> 00:43:36.970
changed as you've gotten
more experience with it?

00:43:39.500 --> 00:43:43.170
DENNIS E. TAYLOR: There are
so many things that change,

00:43:43.170 --> 00:43:46.300
or that you improve
on as you get better.

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:51.840
One of the things that I
find irritating, actually,

00:43:51.840 --> 00:43:55.770
about my first book,
especially now,

00:43:55.770 --> 00:44:00.570
is the degree to which Bob
shrugs, grins, rolls his eyes,

00:44:00.570 --> 00:44:03.150
and stuff like that.

00:44:03.150 --> 00:44:08.010
Those are beats
versus dialogue tags.

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:13.140
Dialogue tags are he said, he
replied, he asked, she shouted,

00:44:13.140 --> 00:44:14.700
stuff like that.

00:44:14.700 --> 00:44:19.950
Beats are where you perform an
action that doesn't necessarily

00:44:19.950 --> 00:44:22.770
relate to what you're actually
saying, but establishes

00:44:22.770 --> 00:44:24.260
who's talking.

00:44:24.260 --> 00:44:27.920
Now, Dennis sat down, then
turned to look at the audience.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:29.130
Hi, I'm me.

00:44:31.770 --> 00:44:36.910
My repertoire for
beats was limited.

00:44:36.910 --> 00:44:39.810
I hope I've improved
on that over time.

00:44:39.810 --> 00:44:41.670
But yeah, that's another thing.

00:44:41.670 --> 00:44:44.880
If I was writing it
again from scratch,

00:44:44.880 --> 00:44:48.230
I would do a lot
better with that.

00:44:48.230 --> 00:44:48.830
All right.

00:44:48.830 --> 00:44:50.150
Well, if There's
no more questions--

00:44:50.150 --> 00:44:51.192
we got one more question.

00:44:53.690 --> 00:44:56.130
AUDIENCE: Any idea when the
Bender books are coming out?

00:44:56.130 --> 00:44:59.863
Is Bender the bad
guy in these ones?

00:44:59.863 --> 00:45:01.280
DENNIS E. TAYLOR:
I had originally

00:45:01.280 --> 00:45:07.160
