00:45:27.482 --> 00:45:29.940
SPEAKER 1: OK, we've got one
more question way in the back.

00:45:32.700 --> 00:45:34.060
Tech guy.

00:45:34.060 --> 00:45:36.450
AUDIENCE: So when
you started writing,

00:45:36.450 --> 00:45:40.140
what did that do to
your habits of reading?

00:45:40.140 --> 00:45:42.090
DENNIS E. TAYLOR: Oh, god.

00:45:42.090 --> 00:45:43.170
Yeah.

00:45:43.170 --> 00:45:47.280
This is a common problem
with writers, actually.

00:45:47.280 --> 00:45:53.562
Once you start learning the
techniques, story arcs, all

00:45:53.562 --> 00:45:55.020
of the things that
go into writing,

00:45:55.020 --> 00:45:58.710
you become very aware of them.

00:45:58.710 --> 00:46:00.150
It's just like--

00:46:00.150 --> 00:46:02.400
SPEAKER 1: Seeing the
sausage being made?

00:46:02.400 --> 00:46:04.200
Seeing the sausage being made?

00:46:04.200 --> 00:46:07.900
DENNIS E. TAYLOR: Yeah, you're
seeing the sausage being made.

00:46:07.900 --> 00:46:11.970
I now find myself much
less tolerant of books,

00:46:11.970 --> 00:46:14.010
and for that matter,
movies and TV

00:46:14.010 --> 00:46:17.790
shows simply because I can see
what the writer is trying to do

00:46:17.790 --> 00:46:20.940
and I can see when they
don't quite pull it off.

00:46:20.940 --> 00:46:24.375
And it can be eye-rolling.

00:46:24.375 --> 00:46:25.250
SPEAKER 1: All right.

00:46:25.250 --> 00:46:25.970
Thank you.

00:46:25.970 --> 00:46:28.650
Well, we really
appreciate having you on.

